<br>
In Velious / Luclin you really needed that extra HP on the main tank, and the extra mana on the clerics.<br>
<br>
Now, with the level cap of 65 (trivializing Luclin / Velious encounters due to increased innate HP / mitigation / mana due to the new level and included AA + new buffs... some of those 50+ man encounters from 6 months ago can now be done with 18 people) those &quot;long&quot; fights don't really need the few main tanks with the high HP, or max FT on the clerics, or the highest mana pools on the wizards for bane.<br>
<br>
With POP, what I have seen is the need for a balanced guild.  A need for everyone to be upgraded, and no classes really favored over others.  Sure, you want those backstab mod weapons going to rogues... and you want those enraging blow weapons on the warriors, and the best DPS bows on the rangers.... but those are very specific cases.   You'll get just as much effectiveness with a 100 or 125 HP breastplate on a paladin or SK as you will a warrior.  Don't brush these classes aside and go with a &quot;Warrior first&quot; mentality, as the ability of these other classes to offtank, and their versatility, make them just as important as everyone else.<br>
<br>
I really think that it is a common misconception that you need all the HP on the main tanks and all the FT on the clerics, etc., as I see people mention this all the time.  Don't fall into that hole, whatever system you use. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rynnia>Rynnia</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Custom title</span><br>  Posts: 1184<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/6/03 6:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> To Baeaan...<br>
<br>
If you are dying because a heal came 1 second too late, you don't need more hitpoints.<br>
<br>
<br>
You need to tighten up that CH circle.<br>
<br>
or<br>
<br>
You need better clerics / clerics with a more reliable connection.<br>
<br>
or<br>
<br>
You should have druids healing you in unison with clerics.<br>
<br>
<br>
You need to over-heal.  I'm a strong supporter of this.  Drown that MT in healing.  The number one thing that will lower DPS / introduce confusion for a raid is a MT death, especially if you are so far above other MT's in your guild as you say you are, if you die, it's gonna hurt.  Whatever chain was setup for you won't work on the next guy to step up.<br>
<br>
Don't go for the longest CH pause you can.  At least half your heals should be hitting for 70% or less of your HP.  If you are dropping below 30% hp often while defensive, tighten up that healing / introduce more healers.  If you think you need a /pause 30 chain, use /pause 20, especially if you can afford it.<br>
<br>
Also... that druid nuking his ass off for a couple hundred DPS just cost you the raid if you died because of a damage spike, and he coulda healed you and saved the MT from death.  Get on them about healing and make sure they heal instead of nuke on anything challenging.  Don't just rely on the cleric chain. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=moontaylesilverleaf>Moontayle Silverleaf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/7/03 5:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=38>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> Requiem moved to  a Point system a few months ago and the hardest part was implementation. We had to take it in stages, so as not to overwhelm people. We spent a month and a half building up points, then on the 1st of the year we started allowing people to use those points. It basically runs like AL's DKP system, but the points come in a bit faster, and the items cost a bit more. We added some special clauses in there that allow people to bid up to twice the base amount for an item if they really want to, and doing this actually helps people as they feel their time raided was well spent. There are some limitations, and we fall back on /random if no one bids at all.<br>
<br>
That said, we're still working out some bugs and it's not perfect. Some of the problems we have run across are different interpretations of the system by the Officers and Raid Leaders, as well as not having an assigned point value for an item that dropped. These are getting worked out though, and like Rynnia said, the good systems adjust as problems arrive, and change over time as the guild moves forward.<br>
<br>
All in all, the Officers of Requiem felt this was a necesary move for the guild. The old system of /random wasn't putting loot into the hands of people who could help the guild. And a system where Officers decided where loot was going would have generated whispers of favortism, and that's a headache no one wants to deal with. So we went points, and it's working out well. Loot gets done quickly, and everyone walks away happy that the items went to the right place.<br>
<br>
That said, no system is perfect, and it's up to the guild to decide what's best for it. <p>- Ignitz Gemcaller, 61st Arch Mage of Requiem<br>
- Gwinie Gemcaller, 57th Druid of Requiem</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sashanna>Sashanna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 244<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/8/03 12:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>summed up: id do dkp if someone else managed it, id never ever ever join a rolling guild, and awarding loot works fine for lazy bastards<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A sophisticated award system can be MUCH more complicated than a DKP system.  DKP tends to only reward attendance with some bonus points occassionally chucked on top for non raid activity.<br>
<br>
A good award system will consider, IMHO, raid attendance, date of most recent loot, size of upgrade, utility, non raid activity, time in guild, number of first tier loots held by that person, relative value of the item based on stats and effects, distribution to non-seniors/infrequent raiders, concentration of loot within specified classes and more. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=felagund>Felagund</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/9/03 4:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:</span><hr size=1> <br>
The main problem with an awards system is that favoritism can &amp; ALWAYS does happen.  It also relies on the dubious principal that the people in charge of the decisions are all seeing/knowing.  Even if the officer DOES keep a spreadsheets on their people &amp; equip, there is going to be times when they aren't on &amp; loot crimes will occur. <br>
<br>
After seeing all systems here used, DKPs are by far the best method for a large guild.  <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=podamandv>PodamanDV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/9/03 5:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The main problem with an awards system is that favoritism can &amp; ALWAYS does happen. It also relies on the dubious principal that the people in charge of the decisions are all seeing/knowing. Even if the officer DOES keep a spreadsheets on their people &amp; equip, there is going to be times when they aren't on &amp; loot crimes will occur. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You're 100% right.  That's the biggest weakness of an assigned loot system.  However, I see the problems of a DKP systems as being worse than the problems with an assigned loot system.  No system is perfect, and it's really a matter of which imperfections you're willing to live with and which you're not.  I think Sashanna laid out the type of thinking that a good award system goes through.   <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.shaw.ca/sapphirez/images/poda-sig.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=boinshar>Boinshar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 236<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/9/03 7:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://frustrated.com/images/boinshar.gif height=102 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> A good loot system is a function of efficiency verses fairness--and to date no one has found the perfect balance, although many make do with what they consider &quot;good enough&quot;.<br>
<br>
In theory, a good loot system should be extremely complicated, taking into account many factors, many of which were listed by others in this post. However, the same loot system would also be tedious to the extreme--a nightmare to impliment and maintain.<br>
<br>
In the end, it's up to the leaders of a guild to decide which characteristics of a loot system is most appealing to them, be it the relatively hands-off maintnance of a DKP system, or the more involved benevolent dictatorship/council. Either way, you will have complaints, but as long as the system serves the purpose of the guild, it's a good system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=skeeja>Skeeja</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/9/03 10:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> RNG has been doing DKP's for nearly one year.  There was much controversy when we switched over to it, and several kinks had to be ironed out, but basically our system works like this:<br>
<br>
You get 4 pts per half hour of raiding, up to 600 points.  Then you hit a soft cap, and get 2 per half hour up to 1200 points, where you hit another soft cap.  After 1200, you get 1pt per half hour.  I have never seen anyone reach the second soft cap.  1000 points is about the most I've ever seen anyone have.<br>
<br>
Our points are visible to all.<br>
<br>
When an item drops, anyone who can equip the item may bid on it.  No matter what it is, with the exception of Blades of Carnage which are deemed Warrior Only.  All other items that drop, if you can use, you can bid.  We find this works best.<br>
<br>
The bidding is silent.  That was specifically put it to stop people from running up the price on someone they didn't like or didn't feel deserved the item.  On most drops we do 2 rounds.  First round bids are taken.  To get a feel of the price.  Then on round 2, a minimum bid is announced, which is runner-up bid +1.  Then another round of bids, then bidding ends.  The winner then receives the item for the runner-up bid +1.<br>
<br>
Spells, Parchments, Quest pieces, or crap loot, we in general just do 1 round to speed up the raid.  It is always announced at the start if it's 1 or 2 rounds.<br>
<br>
Items usable by only 1 or 2 classes, the officers decide a minimum bid that it must go for.  This is announced and then people bid.  If 3+ classes can use it there is no minimum however.<br>
<br>
As the Officer that handles the logs most of the time, I strongly recommend, if you base it on time, that you get a timer, a good one.  I bought a nice one for $12 and it serves me quite well.  I almost never miss any attendances, and when I do it's because I forget to reset it.<br>
And when I do miss one, I get 100 tells asking if I did attendance. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
We don't in general award points for things like VT key camping minor flagging events like the Trials.  In order to earn points, the criteria are that it has to be something requiring a minimum of 18 people.  Now when this was implemented, certain mobs definitely would require 18 people.  However as we got better equipped, mobs that used to require 18+ now can be done with less.  However if 18+ show up, we still will do points.  If it's a raid where no points are awarded...we just use the old /ran 100 method.<br>
<br>
I hope I've answered some of your questions. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=316624">Skeeja Skywolf</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Human Druid of the 65th Era<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Follower of Tunare<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Druid Elder, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.royalnorrathianguard.com">Royal Norrathian Guard</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->&quot;Try not, Do! Or do not. There is no try.&quot;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thebaeaan>The Baeaan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>n00b</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/9/03 11:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> Very enlightening posts all around. <br>
