 <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=8098">f e c k . t h e . d e c e i v e r</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=silkenshammie>Silkenshammie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>n00b</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/13/03 3:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2437.topic&index=46>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> Having seen both award and dKP systems, I'm a strong believer in a well-designed DKP system once a guild hits a certain growth point.  Award is far better in the early life of a guild, but inevitably with time and membership turnover it becomes harder for it to remain objective in the minds of both those awarding loot and those receiving it.<br>
<br>
And to be honest, a well designed DKP system is a powerful motivator.  It certainly has its downsides, but I think people commonly overhype the potential pitfalls.  Of course, designing and refining it is key .. ensuring bidding for alts and twinks is properly controlled, providing the ability to designate certain items as class restricted, and allowing for &quot;non-standard&quot; dkp bonuses for members going above and beyond the call of duty are all crucial.<br>
<br>
The thing is, as a guild becomes accustomed to dkp a lot of the early problems get sorted out.  People soon learn that wasting points on minor upgrades takes them out of the running for major upgrades, and spend time planning and prioritizing where they want to spend - at the same time allowing the newer members space to take what for them are probably major upgrades.  When the PoG clears of the world are called they're less likely to ninjalog because they don't want to miss the dkp.  <br>
<br>
But most importantly, it gives people a sense of control over their destiny.   One of the major downfalls of award loot is that the lootcouncil makes the decisions about what geartypes are important to what classes, and people often feel disempowered by this.   As a classic example, shaman often have widely varying priorities according to their playstyle.  Personally, when I look at gear I look at HP first, resists second and wis/mana/ft are of negligible importance to me.  This is a function of the style I play a shaman.  I know and respect other shaman to whom wis/mana/ft are far more important due to their playstyle.   A lootcouncil will tend to cookiecutter their awards to one style or the other leaving the potential for someone to feel disenfranchised.<br>
<br>
All that being said, the essence of a good loot system is killing lots of mobs.  When a lot of loot is flowing in, there's enough to keep everyone happy <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      It's when times are lean and there's more working than looting that stress gets raised over loot, and at those times imo dkp means at least people can see some asset accruing for them.<br>
 <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=526929" target="_blank">
Silkenshammie Flakes
</a><BR>
Phatarse</a><BR>
